Ford GoBike System Data¶

By Taima Hamadneh¶

Introduction¶

Dataset Introduction:¶

The Ford GoBike System dataset includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area. It captures details such as trip duration, start and end locations, user type, member information, and more.

Preliminary Wrangling¶

# Import the datetime module from Python's standard library
import datetime as dt

# Extract the day from the start day
bike['start_day'] = bike['start_time'].dt.day_name()
# Extract the month from the start day
bike['start_month'] = bike['start_time'].dt.month_name()
# Extract the hour from the start day
bike['start_hr'] = bike['start_time'].dt.hour
# Convert the 'start_hr' column values to strings.
bike['start_hr'] = bike.start_hr.astype(str)

bike['end_day'] = bike['end_time'].dt.day_name()

# Display the number of users using a count plot

plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))     
base_color = sns.color_palette()[0]
ax = sns.countplot(data=bike, x ='user_type', color=base_color)

# Add annotations to the plot
total_points  = bike.shape[0]
category_counts  = bike['user_type'].value_counts()
positions, labels = plt.xticks() # get the current tick locations and labels

# loop through each pair of locations and labels
for position, label in zip(positions, labels):

    # get the text property for the label to get the correct count
    count = category_counts [label.get_text()]
    pct_string = '{}'.format(count)

    # print the annotation just below the top of the bar
    plt.text(position, count-8, pct_string, va='top', ha='center', color = 'w', fontsize=12)

plt.title('Comparison of Bike User Types')

# Remove unnecessary features 
ax.spines['top'].set_visible(False)
ax.spines['right'].set_visible(False)
ax.spines['left'].set_visible(False)
plt.yticks([])
plt.ylabel('')
plt.xlabel('')

# Show the plot
plt.show();

The Relationship Between Trip Duration and User Type?¶

In [17]:
# Convert 'duration_sec' to minutes for better readability
bike['duration_min'] = bike['duration_sec'] / 60

# Create a box plot to visualize trip duration by user type
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.boxplot(data=bike, x='user_type', y='duration_min')
plt.title('Trip Duration by User Type')
plt.xlabel('User Type')
plt.ylabel('Trip Duration (minutes)')
plt.yscale('log')
plt.show()
The box plot reveals a clear difference in trip duration between customer and subscriber user types. Customers tend to have trip durations that are generally shorter than subscribers, likely falling within the range of tens of minutes. Subscribers, on the other hand, exhibit trip durations that span a wider range, potentially extending beyond tens of minutes.¶

Conclusions¶

The dataset covers only the months of February and March in 2019.

The average trip duration is approximately 703 seconds.

User Types: Subscribers dominate the user base, accounting for about 90% of the total users.

Trip Duration Patterns: Subscribers generally have more variable trip durations, while customers tend to have longer, more consistent trips. Younger subscribers have longer trip durations compared to older users.

Gender Differences: The average trip duration is longer for females compared to males, and the "Other" gender group consistently has the longest trip durations across different categories.

Bike Share Trends: Bike-sharing is mostly used by subscribers, and trips tend to be shorter for those using the bike-sharing feature. Most trips are non-bike-sharing, and a significant majority of trips occur between 1 PM and 5 PM.
